ğŸ§° What is There to Use in Three.js?
Hereâ€™s a clear breakdown:

ğŸ”· 1. Core Building Blocks
These are the basics you always need to create a 3D scene:

Part Description
Scene The world where all 3D objects live
Camera What the user sees (like a real camera)
Renderer Converts the 3D scene into pixels on the screen
Mesh A combination of geometry (shape) and material (look)
Light Adds lighting to the scene to make things visible

ğŸ§± 2. Geometry (Shapes)
Use these to create objects:

BoxGeometry â€“ cube or box

SphereGeometry â€“ sphere

PlaneGeometry â€“ flat surface

CylinderGeometry, TorusGeometry, ConeGeometry, etc.

âœ… You can also import 3D models (e.g., .glb/.gltf files)

ğŸ¨ 3. Materials (Looks)
Control how the object appears:

MeshBasicMaterial â€“ no lighting

MeshStandardMaterial â€“ reacts to light (good default)

MeshPhongMaterial â€“ shiny surface

MeshLambertMaterial â€“ softer lighting

ShaderMaterial â€“ advanced custom looks

ğŸ’¡ 4. Lighting
You need lights to see 3D objects unless using MeshBasicMaterial:

AmbientLight â€“ general light

DirectionalLight â€“ like sunlight

PointLight â€“ light from a point

SpotLight â€“ spotlight

HemisphereLight â€“ sky/ground lighting

ğŸŒ 5. Loaders (for Models & Textures)
To import external 3D models and images:

GLTFLoader â€“ for .glb / .gltf (modern 3D format)

TextureLoader â€“ for images (JPEG, PNG)

OBJLoader, FBXLoader â€“ older 3D formats

ğŸ§  6. Controls (for user interaction)
OrbitControls â€“ let users drag and rotate the camera

PointerLockControls â€“ for first-person controls

DragControls â€“ drag objects with the mouse

To use them:

js
Copy
